04684nam a22007335i 9780231555449DE-B159720220426115627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220426t20222022nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2021030689  a97802315554497 a10.7312/wolo204242doi  a(DE-B1597)624610  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aLB875.G542 4aLB875.G542 7aBIO0220002bisacsh04a378.0092aB223/eng/202110061 aWoloch, Nancy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Insider :bA Life of Virginia C. Gildersleeve /cNancy Woloch. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource :b8 black and white figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. Roots: 1877–1911 -- t2. The Insider: 1911 Through World War I -- t3. Gatekeeping: The 1920s -- t4. Emergencies: 1930–1947 -- t5. Embattled: After Barnard, 1947–1965 -- tEndnote: “Working from Within” -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on Sources -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aVirginia C. Gildersleeve was the most influential dean of Barnard College, which she led from 1911 to 1947. An organizer of the Seven College Conference, or “Seven Sisters,” she defended women's intellectual abilities and the value of the liberal arts. She also amassed a strong set of foreign policy credentials and, at the peak of her prominence in 1945, served as the sole woman member of the U.S. delegation to the drafting of the United Nations Charter. But her accomplishments are undercut by other factors: she had a reputation for bias against Jewish applicants for admission to Barnard and early in the 1930s voiced an indulgent view of the Nazi regime.In this biography, historian Nancy Woloch explores Gildersleeve’s complicated career in academia and public life. At once a privileged insider, prone to elitism and insularity, and a perpetual outsider to the sexist establishment in whose ranks she sought to ascend, Gildersleeve stands out as richly contradictory. The book examines her initiatives in higher education, her savvy administration, her strategies for gaining influence in academic life, the ways that she acquired and deployed expertise, and her drive to take part in the world of foreign affairs. Woloch draws out her ambivalent stance in the women’s movement, concerned with women’s status but opposed to demands for equal rights. Tracing resonant themes of ambition, competition, and rivalry, The Insider masterfully weaves Gildersleeve’s life into the histories of education, international relations, and feminism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2022) 0aAntisemitism in higher educationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aDeans (Education)zNew York (State)vBiography. 0aDeans (Education)-New York (State)-Biography. 0aGildersleeve, Virginia Crocheron,-1877-1965. 0aWomen in higher educationzNew York (State)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen's collegeszNew York (State)xHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen's colleges-New York (State)-History-20th century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Women.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311074966340uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/wolo2042440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231555449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231555449/original  a978-3-11-074966-3  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK